{"parse":{"title":"J. Robert Nelson","pageid":56074908,"revid":854092769,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">J. Robert Nelson</span></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span class=\"nickname\">John Robert Nelson</span><br />August 21, 1920<br /><span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Winona_Lake,_Indiana\" title=\"Winona Lake, Indiana\">Winona Lake, Indiana</a>, U.S.</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\nJuly 6, 2004<br /><span class=\"deathplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Houston,_Texas\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Houston, Texas\">Houston, Texas</a>, U.S.</span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Cause&#160;of death</th><td>\ncancer</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Alma&#160;mater</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/DePauw_University\" title=\"DePauw University\">DePauw University</a><br /><a href=\"/wiki/Yale_University\" title=\"Yale University\">Yale University</a><br /><a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Zurich\" title=\"University of Zurich\">University of Zurich</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\nMethodist theologian, academic administrator, ethicist</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"nowrap\">Spouse(s)</span></th><td>\nPatricia Mercer</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Children</th><td>\n2 sons</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>J. Robert Nelson</b> (August 21, 1920 - July 6, 2004) was an American Methodist theologian, academic administrator, and ethicist. He was the dean of the <a href=\"/wiki/Vanderbilt_University_Divinity_School\" title=\"Vanderbilt University Divinity School\">Vanderbilt University Divinity School</a> from 1957 to 1960, and the dean of the <a href=\"/wiki/Boston_University_School_of_Theology\" title=\"Boston University School of Theology\">Boston University School of Theology</a> from 1965 to 1985. He was the author of several books, and published research about the relationship between cloning and Christian ethics.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Early_life\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Early life</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Career\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Career</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Personal_life_and_death\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Personal life and death</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Selected_works\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Selected works</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Early_life\">Early life</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=J._Robert_Nelson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Early life\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>John Robert Nelson was born on August 21, 1920 in <a href=\"/wiki/Winona_Lake,_Indiana\" title=\"Winona Lake, Indiana\">Winona Lake, Indiana</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-heardlibrarypapers_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> He grew up in <a href=\"/wiki/River_Forest,_Illinois\" title=\"River Forest, Illinois\">River Forest, Illinois</a> and was educated in <a href=\"/wiki/Evanston,_Illinois\" title=\"Evanston, Illinois\">Evanston, Illinois</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-houstonchronicleobit_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-houstonchronicleobit-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> He graduated from <a href=\"/wiki/DePauw_University\" title=\"DePauw University\">DePauw University</a> in 1941.<sup id=\"cite_ref-heardlibrarypapers_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> He earned a bachelor of divinity from <a href=\"/wiki/Yale_University\" title=\"Yale University\">Yale University</a> in 1944, and a PhD from the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Zurich\" title=\"University of Zurich\">University of Zurich</a> in 1951.<sup id=\"cite_ref-heardlibrarypapers_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Career\">Career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=J._Robert_Nelson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Nelson was ordained as a Methodist minister in 1944.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> He was a chaplain in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States_Marine_Corps\" title=\"United States Marine Corps\">United States Marine Corps</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/Far_East\" title=\"Far East\">Far East</a> from 1944 to 1946.<sup id=\"cite_ref-heardlibrarypapers_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-houstonchronicleobit_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-houstonchronicleobit-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> He attended the 1948 <a href=\"/wiki/World_Council_of_Churches\" title=\"World Council of Churches\">World Council of Churches</a> and supported <a href=\"/wiki/Ecumenism\" title=\"Ecumenism\">ecumenism</a> throughout his life.<sup id=\"cite_ref-christiancenturyobit_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-christiancenturyobit-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> He was the author and editor of several books. In 1952, he edited <i>The Christian Student and the Church</i>, <i>The Christian Student and the World Struggle</i>, and <i>The Christian Student and the University</i>, a trilogy of essay collections about issues relevant to Christian students.<sup id=\"cite_ref-rossreview_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-rossreview-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> In 1971, he edited a volume about <a href=\"/wiki/Willem_Visser_%27t_Hooft\" title=\"Willem Visser &#39;t Hooft\">Willem Visser 't Hooft</a>, the first secretary general of the World Council of Churches; in a review for the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Journal_of_Church_and_State\" title=\"Journal of Church and State\">Journal of Church and State</a></i>, James Breckenridge called it \"a stimulating collection of essays.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-breckenridgereview_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-breckenridgereview-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Nelson was the dean of the <a href=\"/wiki/Vanderbilt_University_Divinity_School\" title=\"Vanderbilt University Divinity School\">Vanderbilt University Divinity School</a> from 1957 to 1960.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> Nelson initially believed the misleading stories published by Vanderbilt trustee <a href=\"/wiki/James_Geddes_Stahlman\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"James Geddes Stahlman\">James Geddes Stahlman</a>'s newspaper, <i><a href=\"/wiki/Nashville_Banner\" title=\"Nashville Banner\">The Nashville Banner</a></i>, about Civil Rights activist <a href=\"/wiki/James_Lawson_(activist)\" title=\"James Lawson (activist)\">James Lawson</a>, who was a student at the school, which suggested Lawson was inciting others to \"violate the law.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-sumner34_8-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-sumner34-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup> However, when Lawson was expelled by Chancellor <a href=\"/wiki/Harvie_Branscomb\" title=\"Harvie Branscomb\">Harvie Branscomb</a>, Nelson resigned in protest.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> With three of his colleagues, Nelson \"paid Lawson's $500 bail when he was arrested on charges of conspiracy to violate state laws the day after his expulsion.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Nelson served as the dean of the <a href=\"/wiki/Boston_University_School_of_Theology\" title=\"Boston University School of Theology\">Boston University School of Theology</a> from 1965 to 1985.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In the 1970s, he published research about the relationship between cloning and Christian ethics.<sup id=\"cite_ref-chicagotribuneobit_2-7\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-chicagotribuneobit-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> He became the president of the Institute of Religion in Houston in 1985.<sup id=\"cite_ref-houstonchronicleobit_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-houstonchronicleobit-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Personal_life_and_death\">Personal life and death</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=J._Robert_Nelson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Personal life and death\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Nelson married Patricia Mercer in 1945.<sup id=\"cite_ref-houstonchronicleobit_3-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-houstonchronicleobit-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> They had two sons.<sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Nelson died of cancer on July 6, 2004 in Houston, Texas.<sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> His funeral was held at the <a href=\"/wiki/St._Paul%27s_United_Methodist_Church_(Houston)\" title=\"St. Paul&#39;s United Methodist Church (Houston)\">St. Paul's United Methodist Church</a> in Houston.<sup id=\"cite_ref-tennesseanobit_7-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-tennesseanobit-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> His papers are held at the <a href=\"/wiki/Jean_and_Alexander_Heard_Library\" title=\"Jean and Alexander Heard Library\">Jean and Alexander Heard Library</a> on the campus of Vanderbilt University.<sup id=\"cite_ref-heardlibrarypapers_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Selected_works\">Selected works</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=J._Robert_Nelson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Selected works\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert, ed. (1952). <i>The Christian Student and the University</i>. New York: Association Press. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/1106738\">1106738</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Christian+Student+and+the+University&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Association+Press&amp;rft.date=1952&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F1106738&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert, ed. (1952). <i>The Christian Student and the Church</i>. New York: Association Press. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/1942614\">1942614</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Christian+Student+and+the+Church&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Association+Press&amp;rft.date=1952&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F1942614&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert, ed. (1952). <i>The Christian Student and the World Struggle</i>. New York: Association Press. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/808551\">808551</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=The+Christian+Student+and+the+World+Struggle&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Association+Press&amp;rft.date=1952&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F808551&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert (1962). <i>Criterion for the Church</i>. New York: Abingdon. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/155141942\">155141942</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Criterion+for+the+Church&amp;rft.place=New+York&amp;rft.pub=Abingdon&amp;rft.date=1962&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F155141942&amp;rft.aulast=Nelson&amp;rft.aufirst=J.+Robert&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert, ed. (1971). <i>No Man Is Alien: Essays on the Unity of Mankind</i>. Leiden: E.J. Brill. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/496035132\">496035132</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=No+Man+Is+Alien%3A+Essays+on+the+Unity+of+Mankind&amp;rft.place=Leiden&amp;rft.pub=E.J.+Brill&amp;rft.date=1971&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F496035132&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert (1984). <i>Human Life: A Biblical Perspective for Bioethics</i>. Philadelphia, Pennsylvania: Fortress Press. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780800617547\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780800617547\">9780800617547</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/9684882\">9684882</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Human+Life%3A+A+Biblical+Perspective+for+Bioethics&amp;rft.place=Philadelphia%2C+Pennsylvania&amp;rft.pub=Fortress+Press&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F9684882&amp;rft.isbn=9780800617547&amp;rft.aulast=Nelson&amp;rft.aufirst=J.+Robert&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li>\n<li><cite class=\"citation book\">Nelson, J. Robert, ed. (1992). <i>Life as Liberty, Life as Trust</i>. Grand Rapids, Michigan: W.B. Eerdmans. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780802806376\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780802806376\">9780802806376</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/OCLC\" title=\"OCLC\">OCLC</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/oclc/25412351\">25412351</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Life+as+Liberty%2C+Life+as+Trust&amp;rft.place=Grand+Rapids%2C+Michigan&amp;rft.pub=W.B.+Eerdmans&amp;rft.date=1992&amp;rft_id=info%3Aoclcnum%2F25412351&amp;rft.isbn=9780802806376&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AJ.+Robert+Nelson\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=J._Robert_Nelson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-heardlibrarypapers-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-hear